Can the euro be fixed?
Paris-based German Finance Minister Schaeuble recently floated the option of Greece's exit from the euro, hoping to send a signal that no member state is immune to the strict discipline of the currency union.
In reality, his plan sparked a major debate about the principles of the euro, the euro governance model, and the rationale for the euro's existence.
Before the Schäuble Plan was proposed, European leaders had already taken notice of a report on the euro's future written by Commission President Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions two weeks prior. But the new Greek controversy made many policymakers think it was necessary to go back to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they need to share a common currency.
Is this meaningful? Can there be a consensus about Greece's future?
Money is like a nation, it needs a myth to establish it.
Traditionally, it is believed that Germany paid a political price to France in order to reunify under the euro.
In reality, German reunification was only the final step of a project that had been formed as early as the 1980s to solve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with a single market; at the same time they were reluctant to maintain a long-term currency mechanism dominated by the German central bank.
A true European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In retrospect, German reunification has turned out to be more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was in an overvaluation state, with its economy facing great difficulties; France was in an undervaluation state, with its economy thriving.
In the following decade, the imbalance gradually arose between the newly rising Germany and the countries that experienced a credit boom due to low interest rates.
As the 2008 global financial crisis broke out, these conditions became the cradle of the perfect storm.
Nobody knows what Europe will be like without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark overvalue further?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analytical baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
This is not a reason for complacency.
In the past 15 years, the economic performance of the eurozone has consistently been disappointing, and its political system must be held accountable for this.
What's really important is whether the common European currency still matters in the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is too high to imagine (and if the eurozone were to collapse during a crisis and exacerbated the mutual recriminations between participating countries, the cost would be even higher).
In addition, abandoning the euro may unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke at Oxford University has recently pointed out that this view is not comprehensive.
In a logical sense, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should keep their marriage going because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still have meaning?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It is assumed that the single currency can promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the other hand, intra-Eurozone trade and investment growth is lackluster, with growth potential actually weakened in the process.
This part is because the national government is not going further on the basis of monetary unification, to build the Eurozone into a super economic power, but instead trying to preserve the remaining power.
This may be in line with economic logic, but in economic terms, it is of no avail: a huge internal market of Europe is one of its main assets, and it cannot afford to waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
In addition, people hope the euro to become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries can meet the necessary legal, market, and policy systems).
While according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been largely achieved.
The euro's international usage ranks second only to the US dollar, and this achievement helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an insignificant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) believe that the institutions based on the euro will improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the overall policy level of Europe is naturally higher than that of countries.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test arrived: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, so its performance was not as good as that of the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring about prosperity, it must further introduce policy institutional reforms.
But establishing and implementing a schedule must be based on a broad consensus of the nature of the problem.
The persistent debate on the Greek issue shows that Europe still has a long way to go before reaching a consensus: participating countries' analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis are mutually contradictory, so their proposed remedies are also mutually contradictory.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University has observed that in the early stages of international cooperation on public health, the governance of global diseases was severely hampered by the different infectious patterns found in various countries.
Each country favors joint action, but is unable to form a uniform plan, because they have different opinions on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone is facing today.
Fortunately, this problem is not insoluble, as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of the banking union have shown.
Divergence has not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, which shows that institutional governance is indeed important.
However, reform and action did not begin until recently, and were implemented only under the pressure of a severe crisis, a fact that has made us realize the difficulty of achieving consensus.
Europe can no longer procrastinate and pretend.
Eurozone member states must establish a united schedule for governance and political reform, turning the currency union into a thriving engine, or else they will be doomed to sink in repeated debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose trust.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussion and grand reform.
Nowadays, all major parties have a duty to clarify what is indispensable to them, what is unacceptable, and what they are willing to trade in order to get what they want.
